            "content": "# Patterns and conventions\n\n## Error handling\n\nThe project has a strict error hierarchy defined in `@factory/logging/errors`. Never use the vanilla `Error` class.\n\n```ts\nimport {\n  MetaError,\n  ResponseError400BadRequest,\n  ResponseError404NotFound,\n  // ... other ResponseError classes\n} from '@factory/logging/errors';\n\nimport { logInfo, logWarn, logException } from '@factory/logging';\n```\n\n**Core rules:**\n\n1. **Bubble by default** — do not wrap with `try/catch` unless you have a concrete reason (fallback value, error translation, or a handled null return).\n2. **Use typed errors** — internal 500s use `MetaError`; non-200 user responses use the matching `ResponseErrorXXX` class.\n3. **Breadcrumbs, not noise** — use `logInfo`/`logWarn` before risky calls to leave context. Never call `logError`.\n4. **One or the other** — if you call `logException`, you handle the error locally (no rethrow). Otherwise, rethrow without logging.\n5. **Preserve the original stack** — rethrow the original error object; only create a new error when semantics change.\n\nSee `docs/error-handling.md` for the complete guide.\n\n## File organization\n\nESLint enforces these rules via `packages/eslint-config`:\n\n- Enums go in `enums.ts`, types go in `types.ts`\n- API types go in `packages/common/src/api/{service}/types.ts`\n- Use absolute imports (`@factory/...`, `@/...`) — no relative imports beyond one level\n- No `require()` — use ES6 imports\n\nSee `docs/file-organization.md` for details.\n\n## UI components\n\nNever use bare HTML elements. Use `@factory/core-ui` primitives:\n\n| HTML | core-ui equivalent |\n|------|-------------------|\n| `<div>` | `<Box>` |\n| `<button>` | `<Button>` |\n| `<input>` | `<Input>` |\n| `<p>`, `<span>` | `<Text>` |\n| `<h1>`–`<h6>` | `<Header>` |\n\nNever hardcode colors. Use `colors.semantics.*` from the design system.\n\nSee `docs/ui-development.md` for the full guide.\n\n## State management (frontend)\n\nUse Redux Toolkit. Select state precisely — not by destructuring the whole slice:\n\n```ts\n// Wrong\nconst { messageTree } = useSelector((state: RootState) => state.assembly);\n\n// Correct\nconst messageTree = useSelector((state: RootState) => state.assembly.messageTree);\n```\n\n## Feature flags\n\nAdd new flags to the Statsig console, then define them in `packages/common/src/feature-flags/constants.ts`:\n\n```ts\nexport const FactoryFeatureFlags = {\n  MyFeature: {\n    displayName: 'My Feature',\n    statsigName: 'my_feature',\n    defaultValue: false,\n  },\n};\n```\n\nUse `useFeatureFlagValue(FactoryFeatureFlags.MyFeature)` in React components, or `getFeatureFlagInstance()` on the backend. See `docs/feature-flags.md`.\n\n## Component structure\n\n- Maximum 200–300 lines per component\n- Extract repeated hooks into custom hooks\n- No utility functions inside component files — put them in a `utils/` file\n- Use CSS-driven interactions (animations, show/hide) rather than component state where possible\n\n## Naming conventions\n\n- File names: `camelCase.ts` for modules, `PascalCase.tsx` for React components\n- Test files colocated: `service.ts` → `service.test.ts`\n- Enum files: `enums.ts` in each feature directory\n- Type files: `types.ts` in each feature directory\n",
