            "content": "# Tools\n\nTools are the capabilities Droid exposes to the LLM. Each tool has a name, a description, a JSON Schema for its input, and an execute function. The LLM chooses which tools to call based on the task; `droid-core` runs the execute function and returns the result.\n\n## Built-in tools\n\nTool definitions live in `packages/droid-core/src/tools/definitions/`:\n\n### File tools (`definitions/file-tools/`)\n\n| Tool | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `Read` | Read a file's contents (with line offset/limit) |\n| `Edit` | Find-and-replace text in a file |\n| `MultiEdit` | Multiple find-and-replace operations in one call |\n| `Create` | Create a new file with specified content |\n\n### Search tools\n\n| Tool | File | Purpose |\n|------|------|---------|\n| `Grep` | `grepSearch.ts` | ripgrep-powered content search |\n| `Glob` | `globSearch.ts` | File path search with glob patterns |\n\n### Shell tool\n\n| Tool | File | Purpose |\n|------|------|---------|\n| `Execute` | `shell.ts` | Run a shell command |\n\n### Navigation tools\n\n| Tool | File | Purpose |\n|------|------|---------|\n| `LS` | `viewFolder.ts` | List directory contents |\n| `ViewFile` | `viewFile.ts` | Quick file preview |\n\n### Mission tools (`definitions/mission/`)\n\nTools specific to the spec/mission workflow — creating specs, validating plans, and tracking progress.\n\n### Web tools (`definitions/web/`)\n\nTools for fetching web content and searching the web.\n\n### Slack tools (`definitions/slack/`)\n\nTools for reading Slack channels and threads (when Slack is connected).\n\n### Todo tool (`definitions/todo/`)\n\nThe `TodoWrite` tool for managing a structured task list during sessions.\n\n### CLI-specific tools (`definitions/cli/`)\n\nAdditional tools registered only in the CLI context (not available in all environments).\n\n## Tool registry\n\n`src/tools/registry.ts` maintains the global tool registry. Tools are registered by name and looked up by the agent when assembling a request:\n\n```ts\n// Registration\nregistry.register(ReadTool);\n\n// Lookup\nconst tool = registry.get('Read');\n```\n\nThe registry returns the tool schema (for inclusion in the LLM request) and the execute function (for running the tool call result).\n\n## Adding a new tool\n\n1. Create a file in `src/tools/definitions/` (or a subdirectory for grouped tools).\n2. Use `createTool()` from `src/tools/create-tool.ts` to define the tool.\n3. Register the tool in `src/tools/definitions/index.ts`.\n4. If the tool is CLI-only, register it in the CLI-specific definitions.\n\nThe `createTool` helper provides type inference for the input schema:\n\n```ts\nimport { createTool } from '../create-tool';\n\nexport const MyTool = createTool({\n  name: 'MyTool',\n  description: 'Does something useful',\n  inputSchema: {\n    type: 'object',\n    properties: {\n      target: { type: 'string', description: 'The target' },\n    },\n    required: ['target'],\n  },\n  execute: async ({ target }) => {\n    return `Result for ${target}`;\n  },\n});\n```\n\n## Tool permissions\n\nSome tools require user confirmation before executing (notably `Execute` for shell commands and `Create`/`Edit` for file writes). The CLI manages this through the permission flow in `src/commands/resolveToolSelection.ts`.\n\n## Native tools\n\n`src/tools/definitions/native-tools.ts` registers tools that wrap native platform capabilities (like `ripgrep` for `Grep`). The CLI embeds the `ripgrep` binary in `apps/cli/src/embed-native-libs.ts`.\n",
