            "content": "# Fun facts\n\n## The TUI is a React app\n\n`apps/cli/src/app.tsx` is a ~161 KB React component that renders entirely in a terminal. When you use `droid` interactively, you're running React — just with `stdout` instead of a DOM. Ink handles reconciliation and maps React elements to ANSI escape codes.\n\n## The daemon can live inside the CLI\n\n`packages/daemon-core` is designed to run in two contexts: as a standalone `factoryd` process, or embedded directly inside `apps/cli`. This means the CLI can run agent sessions entirely locally without a separately installed daemon.\n\n## The CLI ships as a single executable\n\nThe final `droid` binary is a Node.js Single Executable Application (SEA). Everything — the TypeScript, native binaries like `ripgrep` and `keytar`, sounds, and i18n strings — gets bundled into a single ~50 MB file. The build system detects your platform and produces the right binary automatically.\n\n## ripgrep is embedded in the binary\n\nBecause the `Grep` tool uses ripgrep for fast file search, and ripgrep is a native binary, the CLI embeds it directly in the SEA bundle. `apps/cli/src/embed-native-libs.ts` and `apps/daemon/src/embed-native-libs.ts` both handle this at startup.\n\n## Signal spawns a Droid to create Linear tickets\n\nThe `analyze_and_ticket` mode in `apps/signal` doesn't just detect friction patterns — it spawns a Droid agent (the same AI that writes your code) with read-only BigQuery access and asks it to analyze friction data and create Linear tickets. The AI is debugging itself.\n\n## The relay multiplexes N clients onto one daemon\n\nThe relay service has no persistent storage. It's a pure in-memory WebSocket multiplexer. `ChannelRegistry` is just a `Map<computerId, ChannelSession>` in RAM. If the relay restarts, all connections drop and clients reconnect.\n\n## The wiki system uses itself\n\nThe `wiki-upload` command that uploads documentation to Factory is documented in this very wiki, which was generated and uploaded using the same command.\n",
