            "content": "# Exec mode\n\nExec mode runs the Droid agent without a TUI. The agent executes a task and exits, making it suitable for CI pipelines, scripts, and programmatic use.\n\n## Invocation\n\n```bash\ndroid exec --prompt \"Add unit tests for src/auth.ts\"\n\n# With options\ndroid exec \\\n  --prompt \"Fix the failing tests\" \\\n  --model claude-3-5-sonnet \\\n  --autonomy high \\\n  --output-format json \\\n  --output-file result.json\n```\n\n## Exec runners\n\nThere are two exec runner implementations:\n\n### `streamingJsonRpcExecRunner.ts`\n\n`apps/cli/src/exec/streamingJsonRpcExecRunner.ts` — the primary exec runner. Used when the CLI is connected to the daemon (standard deployment). Receives messages over stdin/stdout JSON-RPC 2.0 and sends notifications back.\n\nThis is the runner active in normal sessions (interactive or exec mode when launched through the daemon).\n\n### `renderlessExecRunner.ts`\n\n`apps/cli/src/exec/renderlessExecRunner.ts` — a standalone runner that doesn't require a daemon connection. Used for direct CLI invocations where the daemon is not in the path.\n\n### Shared logic\n\n`apps/cli/src/exec/sharedAgentRunner.ts` contains logic shared between both runners: prompt building, tool resolution, LLM call orchestration, and result collection.\n\n## Output formats\n\n| Format | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `text` (default) | Human-readable progress output to stdout |\n| `json` | Structured JSON output with the full execution result |\n\nThe JSON output includes the final message, tool calls made, usage statistics, and any error information. This is consumed by CI workflows and the Factory platform's eval system.\n\n## Autonomy modes\n\nThe `--autonomy` flag controls how the agent handles tool confirmation. From most to least restrictive:\n\n| Mode | Behavior |\n|---|---|\n| `default` | Standard confirmation behavior — risky tools require approval |\n| `low` | Confirms more actions than default |\n| `medium` | Confirms fewer actions than default |\n| `high` | Only confirms the riskiest actions |\n| `full` | No confirmations — agent runs fully autonomously |\n\nIn exec mode, if the agent requests confirmation and no UI is available, the runner rejects or auto-approves based on the autonomy setting.\n\n## Tool selection\n\nUse `--tool` flags to allow or block specific tools:\n\n```bash\n# Allow only specific tools\ndroid exec --prompt \"...\" --tool Execute --tool Read\n\n# Block dangerous tools\ndroid exec --prompt \"...\" --no-tool Execute\n```\n\nTool selection logic is in `apps/cli/src/commands/resolveToolSelection.ts`.\n\n## Session context\n\nExec mode can resume an existing session:\n\n```bash\ndroid exec --session-id abc123 --prompt \"Continue where we left off\"\n```\n\nOr start fresh (default). The session is stored in Firestore via the backend API.\n\n## BYOK (Bring Your Own Key)\n\nThe `--byok` flag routes LLM requests directly to a provider using the caller's API key, bypassing Factory's LLM proxy:\n\n```bash\ndroid exec --prompt \"...\" --byok --api-key sk-...\n```\n\nThis is implemented in `apps/cli/src/commands/exec.ts` and controlled by the `exec-byok` feature.\n\n## Exit codes\n\n| Code | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| 0 | Success — agent completed the task |\n| 1 | Error — agent failed, system error, or auth failure |\n| 2 | Interrupted — execution was cancelled |\n\nSee `apps/cli/src/exec/types.ts` for the `ExecRunResult` and `DroidExecutionStatus` types.\n",
