            "content": "# Deployment\n\nFactory has multiple deployment targets, each with its own pipeline.\n\n## Backend and web app\n\nBoth `apps/backend` and `apps/web` deploy to **Vercel**.\n\n| App | Workflow | Trigger |\n|---|---|---|\n| `apps/backend` | `deploy-prod.yml` | Merge to `main` |\n| `apps/web` | `deploy-prod-app.yml` | Merge to `main` |\n| `apps/admin` | `deploy-prod-admin.yml` | Merge to `main` |\n| Dev deployments | `deploy-dev-web.yml` | Push to `dev` |\n\nThe Vercel configuration is in `vercel.json` at the app root. Each app deploys independently.\n\n## Environments\n\n| Environment | Branch / Trigger | URL pattern |\n|---|---|---|\n| Production | `main` | `api.factory.ai`, `app.factory.ai` |\n| Dev | `dev` | Dev-specific subdomains |\n| Staging | PR previews | Vercel preview URLs |\n| Localhost | Local dev | `localhost:3000`, `localhost:3002` |\n\nFeature flag evaluation uses Statsig environment tiers that map to these environments (see `docs/feature-flags.md`).\n\n## CLI binary distribution\n\nThe `droid` CLI distributes as a Single Executable Application (SEA) for five platforms:\n\n| Platform | Workflow | Distribution |\n|---|---|---|\n| macOS ARM64 | `cli-release.yml` | GitHub Releases, npm |\n| macOS x64 | `cli-release.yml` | GitHub Releases, npm |\n| Linux ARM64 | `cli-release.yml` | GitHub Releases, npm |\n| Linux x64 | `cli-release.yml` | GitHub Releases, npm |\n| Windows x64 | `cli-release.yml` | GitHub Releases, npm |\n\nThe CLI also publishes to npm as `@factory-ai/cli` via `cli-release-npm.yml`.\n\nAuto-update works via `apps/cli/src/commands/update.ts`, which downloads new binaries from `downloads.factory.ai`.\n\n## Daemon binary distribution\n\nThe `factoryd` daemon distributes as a standalone binary via `factoryd-release.yml`. It is:\n\n- Bundled inside the desktop Electron app\n- Downloaded to remote CDEs from `downloads.factory.ai`\n\nThe daemon has its own auto-update mechanism — on each startup, it checks `downloads.factory.ai` for a newer version and replaces itself if one is found.\n\n## Desktop app distribution\n\nThe Electron desktop app distributes via:\n\n| Platform | Format | Workflow |\n|---|---|---|\n| macOS | `.dmg` | `desktop-release.yml` |\n| Windows | `.exe` (NSIS) | `desktop-release.yml` |\n| Linux | `.AppImage` | `desktop-release.yml` |\n\nThe desktop app has an auto-updater that checks for new versions and installs them in the background.\n\n## Infrastructure\n\nCloud infrastructure (VPCs, databases, CDN, compute) is managed with **OpenTofu** (open-source Terraform fork). Infrastructure configs are in `infra/`. To validate changes:\n\n```bash\ncd infra && tofu init\ntofu validate\ntofu fmt\n```\n\nThe `opentofu.yml` workflow runs `tofu plan` on infrastructure PRs.\n\n## Release process\n\nReleases follow a structured process:\n\n1. **Release cut** (`release-cut.yml`) — creates a release branch, bumps version numbers\n2. **Binary builds** — each app/binary builds in CI\n3. **Binary release** (`binary-release-env.yml`) — publishes artifacts to GitHub Releases and S3\n4. **Post-release validation** (`post-release-validation.yml`) — smoke tests against the released binaries\n\n## Hotfixes\n\nFor urgent production fixes, use the `hotfix-cut.yml` workflow to cherry-pick commits onto `main` directly, bypassing the normal dev→main cycle.\n",
