            "content": "# Security\n\nFactory handles sensitive user data (code, credentials, LLM API keys) and makes potentially destructive actions on behalf of users (file edits, shell commands). Security is enforced at multiple layers.\n\n## Authentication\n\nAll backend API requests require authentication via WorkOS AuthKit. The Next.js middleware at `apps/backend/src/middleware.ts` validates session tokens on every request before routing to handlers. Unauthenticated requests receive `401 Unauthorized`.\n\nThe CLI stores auth tokens in the OS keychain via `@factory/runtime/auth` (using `keytar` on macOS/Windows/Linux). Tokens are never written to plain files.\n\n## Authorization\n\nOrganization-level access control ensures users can only access their own org's data. All Firestore queries include the `orgId` as a filter condition. The backend service layer enforces this — API handlers call services that always scope queries to the authenticated org.\n\n## Tool confirmation (agent actions)\n\nBefore the agent executes potentially destructive actions (shell commands, file edits), it requests user approval. This is the primary security mechanism for agent-side risk — the user remains in control of what the agent does to their system.\n\nThe confirmation system (`apps/cli/src/agent/tool-confirmation.ts`) distinguishes between read-only operations (no confirmation needed) and write/execute operations (confirmation required unless autonomy mode overrides it).\n\n## Secrets management\n\n- LLM provider API keys are stored server-side in environment variables; clients never receive them\n- The logging system automatically scrubs secrets from log messages (`@factory/logging`)\n- Environment variables are accessed through `@factory/environment`, not `process.env` directly\n- Firestore security rules (`firestore.rules`) restrict direct client access\n\n## Input validation\n\nAll API route handlers validate input types. JSON schemas in `packages/common/src/droid/schemas/` validate protocol messages at the daemon boundary. Zod schemas validate LLM streaming events.\n\n## Fraud detection\n\nThe backend includes a fraud detection layer (`apps/backend/src/services/fraud/`) that runs heuristics during account creation and session initialization to detect abuse.\n\n## Endor Labs dependency scanning\n\nThe `endor-labs.yml` CI workflow scans dependencies for known vulnerabilities on each PR.\n\n## Content Security Policy\n\nThe web and desktop apps enforce CSP headers to prevent XSS. The desktop app's CSP configuration is in `apps/desktop/src/main/csp-sync.test.ts` (CSP sync test ensures the renderer and main process CSPs stay consistent).\n\n## Webhook signature verification\n\nIncoming webhooks (GitHub, WorkOS, Orb) are verified using HMAC signatures before processing. Webhook handlers at `apps/backend/src/app/api/webhooks/` reject unsigned requests.\n\n## Trust boundaries\n\n| Boundary | How it's secured |\n|---|---|\n| Frontend → Backend | WorkOS session token (HTTP-only cookie) |\n| Frontend → Daemon | WebSocket connection authenticated per session |\n| Backend → LLM providers | Server-side API keys, never exposed to clients |\n| Backend → Firestore | Service account credentials via GCP IAM |\n| CLI → Backend | Bearer token stored in OS keychain |\n| Daemon → CLI | Local stdin/stdout (process isolation) |\n",
