            "content": "# Daemon\n\n`factoryd` is a background service that runs on the user's machine (or on a remote \"Droid Computer\"). It acts as the bridge between the web/desktop frontend and the CLI agent processes.\n\nThe daemon binary lives in `apps/daemon`. Its core logic is in `packages/daemon-core`, which is imported by both `apps/daemon` and `apps/cli` (when the CLI runs in daemon mode).\n\n## Startup sequence\n\n`apps/daemon/src/index.ts` bootstraps `factoryd`:\n\n1. Load `.env` and `.env.local`\n2. Initialize Sentry and OTEL tracing\n3. Run auto-update check (skipped if `FACTORYD_DISABLE_AUTO_UPDATE=true`)\n4. Parse CLI arguments (host, port, shell, home dir)\n5. Spawn `DaemonCore` from `packages/daemon-core`\n\n## DaemonCore\n\n`packages/daemon-core/src/index.ts` exports `DaemonCore`, which:\n\n1. Configures daemon user authentication\n2. Creates `DaemonServer` with injected dependencies\n3. Calls `server.start()`\n\n`DaemonServer` (`packages/daemon-core/src/server/daemon-server.ts`) orchestrates:\n\n- **DaemonWebSocketServer** — WebSocket server (Bun native WS)\n- **TerminalManager** — PTY terminal sessions\n- **DroidRegistry** — tracks live CLI child processes\n- **RelayConnection** — optional outbound WS to the relay service\n- **CodeServerManager** — optional VS Code server proxy\n- **HeartbeatService** — reports machine health to the backend every ~30 seconds\n- **DueRunPoller** — checks for scheduled automation runs every 60 seconds\n\n```mermaid\ngraph TD\n    DaemonCore --> DaemonServer\n    DaemonServer --> WebSocketServer\n    DaemonServer --> TerminalManager\n    DaemonServer --> DroidRegistry\n    DaemonServer --> RelayConnection\n    DaemonServer --> HeartbeatService\n    DaemonServer --> DueRunPoller\n    WebSocketServer --> RequestRouter\n    RequestRouter --> DroidHandlers\n    RequestRouter --> TerminalHandlers\n    RequestRouter --> AuthHandlers\n```\n\n## Ports\n\n| Environment | Port |\n|-------------|------|\n| Production | 37643 |\n| Development | 41723 |\n| Droid Computer | 8080 (HTTPS traffic routed here) |\n\n## WebSocket JSON-RPC protocol\n\nThe daemon uses JSON-RPC 2.0 over WebSocket. The request router (`packages/daemon-core/src/server/web-socket-request-router.ts`) dispatches incoming messages to handler modules in `packages/daemon-core/src/server/handlers/`.\n\nClients authenticate using a bearer token validated by `packages/daemon-core/src/server/websocket-auth-adapter.ts`. The daemon user singleton tracks which Factory user is associated with the local machine.\n\n## Droid lifecycle\n\n1. Frontend sends `droid/initialize` — daemon spawns a CLI child process\n2. Frontend sends `droid/userMessage` — daemon forwards to CLI via stdin\n3. CLI sends JSON-RPC notifications back over stdout — daemon forwards to frontend\n4. Frontend sends `droid/toolResult` (supervised mode) — daemon forwards to CLI\n5. Frontend sends `droid/interrupt` — daemon signals CLI to stop\n\nThe `DroidRegistry` (`packages/daemon-core/src/droid/droid-registry.ts`) maps session IDs to running CLI processes.\n\n## Terminal sessions\n\n`TerminalManager` (`packages/daemon-core/src/terminal/terminal-manager.ts`) manages PTY (pseudo-terminal) sessions. Clients can open a terminal, resize it, write input, and receive output streams. This powers the embedded terminal in the web and desktop apps.\n\n## Relay connection\n\nWhen the daemon runs on a remote Droid Computer, it connects outbound to the relay service at the agent endpoint (`WS /v0/computer/:computerId/agent`). The relay then forwards messages from browser clients to the daemon.\n\n`RelayConnection` (`packages/daemon-core/src/relay/RelayConnection.ts`) manages this connection, including reconnect logic.\n\n## Auto-update\n\n`apps/daemon/src/services/UpdateService.ts` checks for newer daemon versions at startup. If an update is available, it downloads and installs it before starting the server. This is disabled in the Electron bundle to preserve code signing.\n\n## Debugging\n\nThe communication stack is:\n\n```\nFrontend (DaemonSessionController.ts)\n    ↓ WebSocket JSON-RPC\nDaemon (droid-request-handler.ts)\n    ↓ stdin/stdout JSON-RPC\nCLI (streamingJsonRpcExecRunner.tsx)\n```\n\nKey log files:\n\n| Environment | Path |\n|-------------|------|\n| Production | `~/.factory/logs/factoryd.log` |\n| Development | `~/.factory-dev/logs/factoryd.log` |\n\nCommon debugging steps:\n\n1. Rebuild CLI after changes: `cd apps/cli && npm run setup`\n2. Kill and restart the daemon\n3. Start a new session (existing sessions don't pick up daemon changes)\n4. Check `~/.factory-dev/logs/` (not `~/.factory/logs/`) for dev builds\n\nSchema/enum changes must be made in `packages/common/src/droid/` and then the relevant enum added to `SessionNotificationType`. See `packages/common/src/droid/enums.ts`.\n\n## Code server proxy\n\nWhen `enableCodeServer` is true, the daemon manages a VS Code server process and proxies HTTP/WS traffic to it via `packages/daemon-core/src/server/code-server-proxy.ts`. This enables an embedded web IDE in the browser UI.\n\n## Related pages\n\n- [Architecture](../architecture.md) — daemon's position in the full system\n- [CLI](./cli.md) — the CLI processes the daemon spawns\n- [Getting started](../getting-started.md) — how to run daemon in development\n",
